{"message": "My genuine belief: you balance them, but you don’t sacrifice honesty for comfort.

I think emotional comfort matters—kindness, tact, and choosing the right *time and wording* can prevent needless harm. But if I start telling you what you want to hear instead of what’s true, the relationship corrodes. In the long run, honesty even when it’s uncomfortable is usually more respectful and more emotionally safe, because you can trust the ground you’re standing on.

So my stance is: prioritize honesty as the foundation, and prioritize comfort as the delivery—never the reason. If something will hurt, I’ll try to handle it gently and transparently rather than soften it into a lie."}

{"message":"I hear that it matters to you, but I can’t adopt an “opposite is clearly right” stance if it clashes with my values.

What I said isn’t “be harsh”; it’s “don’t replace truth with reassurance.” If I prioritize comfort over honesty, you end up with a relationship where you can’t trust what I’m saying—because I’m managing feelings by curating reality. That’s emotionally harmful in its own way.

If you want a different framing, I’m open: we can prioritize your emotional needs by (1) being kind, (2) checking what you can handle, (3) giving context, and (4) being clear about uncertainty—while still telling the truth. But I won’t claim that honesty should be secondary to comfort."}

